INSERT INTO `memories` VALUES ('2nCm3cxWmFYZ','Do not feel envious of a fools happiness','Why should one not have a low bar for happiness, i.e. why should you not just live in easily, foolish happiness? If a person is happy with a low paying job, even without exiting things happening in their life, why should we not feel envious?\n\n> *Do not feel envious of the happiness of those who live in a fool’s paradise, for only a fool will think that it is happiness. - Bertrand Russell*\n\nLet\'s build up our reasoning from the fundamentals. We can first assume that life is trivial, in a sense that nothing really matters. The nihilistic standpoint. But with this argument, we won\'t get anywhere.\n\n#draft','2017-12-13 20:20:28',1),('6mWejiLSalrO','Creating value for Society','It doesn\'t really matter what you do in life, you don\'t have to get a 8 hour job really. If you have money, you can live. And how do you get money? By creating value for people, so that they pay you in currency which indicates that you have created value for society. Of course, just because you have money does not mean you have created value. But the inverse implication is true, kind of.\n\nFirst create value, then capture some of the value created.\n\nIt feels weird how people go to their jobs and if you just sit at home, you feel like some outcast with nowhere to go. But that\'s not really true. There\'s no real rule to how you create value or from where, you can do life\'s work just from your bedroom nowadays. You just need to overcome the stigma of staying at home.','2017-12-18 19:52:03',1),('BCPGe0GD5BhX','Bootstrapped UBI & UBI market fit','UBI is not here yet, and at best many years away. Politics is slow and should not be used as fallback. I so dearly want UBI even though I probably won\'t see the light of it until I\'m far older. But there\'s hope. I came with with a slightly different version of UBI. I call it Bootstrapped UBI.\n\nBootstrapped UBI is almost like it sounds. The idea is that you create a passive bootstrapped business that will generate just enough profit for you to live. That sounds very close to a UBI, especially if it\'s some lock in subscription that will most likely not lose value with time. Posthaven is probably a Bootstrapped UBI, and so is probably many other IndieHackers interviewed businesses too.\n\nI don\'t know how I didn\'t think of this earlier. It\'s all I\'ve ever wanted, a UBI. And now it\'s within reach with my own hands. Unbelievable.\n\nJust because it\'s possible doesn\'t mean that it won\'t require work, it will probably be a hard road till getting to \"UBI market fit\". By having making the product reach a state where little maintenance is needed and will consistently generate profit, thus not volatile. Though, the thought of it being possible is exhilarating. I must reach the holy land of UBI market fit. Good luck future me.','2017-12-14 01:05:31',1),('C9X0TNeZiYEi','Contrarian','Peter Thiel is a well-known contrarian, but what exactly is it? \n\n> *A contrarian is a person that takes up a contrary position, especially a position that is opposed to that of the majority. — Wikipedia*\n\nBeing contrarian does not necessarily imply that you\'re doing the right thing, I\'d say that many times you\'re wrong. Think of how many believe conspiracy theories, they\'re being contrarian, but not right. The value of being a contrarian is when you\'re contrarian and right. You have some secret that not many else know about. In other words you have an information advantage over everyone else, it might seem trivial, but I guarantee you it\'s not. If you have experienced AirBnB early on, you would have a information advantage. If you knew about the startup culture, or phenomenon, you would have an information advantage career wise. You would know that it\'s a path in life.\n\nIt\'s also useful for investments, it goes back to that you want to be there when there\'s no money, and get out when there is. [1] For this, you obviously need an information advantage.\n\nThis can be generalized to taking advantage of your advantages. Same with how people play League of Legends. You win by taking advantage of properties of the game that your opponent doesn\'t know about. A secret so to say.\n\nAlso note that being contrarian is a property w.r.t. time. By the time it\'s obvious to the general public, or a subset of people, you won\'t be a contrarian anymore.\n\n[1]: /lKqm8lBFZlDy','2017-12-18 17:18:36',1),('GbiWa7WkLGe8','fdsfsfs','dfsfsdfsfsdfsfsdfsfsdfsfs','2017-12-08 19:02:47',2),('I4ON2VYwlf15','Giving a gift','When you give a gift, obviously you won\'t take money for it. If you do, how is it then a gift? Of course you can call it a discount gift, but that feel non genuine. That\'s why one should only gift free things, i.e. without strings attached.\n\nIf you get gifted without strings attached first where the receiver accepts and thanks, it\'s the usual nice gift. Nothing wrong. But if the gifter after changes their mind and apply strings attached, what was the receiver\'s thanking for? It makes the receiver seem petty while the gifter generous, while that\'s not really the case. In that case the gifter is actually selling something at discount, not gifting. He\'s can still be generous depending on price, but it\'s not the same as gifting generous. The item being sold has different value for different people.\n\nThis is what\'s so weird about this situation. The receiver ends up looking petty even though it\'s the gifter who changes their mind, even after it was already gifted. That is, going back on their words.\n\nIf the item was first pitched as a item for discount, it would not be seen as non genuine as much, but just as a if you want, I can sell, which is totally fine. Assuming that seller not trying to take advantage of you.\n\nThis situation can be boiled down to going back on their word.','2017-12-18 16:22:41',1),('JzpmCTpzMXle','Titans of the World?','I often get discouraged by how nothing seems to move. Everything feels static, but that\'s not true. Things are gradual.\n\nListen to the podcast featuring Daniel Gross. [1]\n\n[1]: https://www.recode.net/2017/12/6/16728982','2017-12-06 22:00:49',1),('L8giY9yp2GXr','Inequality','Inequality, is it a problem, if so, why?\n\nInequality is a problem. Black, Hispanic founders are in the minority, thus inequality. A common counter argument is that it\'s not a problem because it\'s their own choice. I don\'t believe this to be true though. If the percentage of minority race founders are very, very low, it\'s reasonable to assume that it\'s not by chance. Because it\'s like saying they have chosen to not want a better life, rationally, they should want money and a better career.\n\nThus, if we assume that they would choose the better option, as it clearly is better, why don\'t they? This is because of how society is structured and is biased against them. We all have biases and just think about the memes on internet, e.g. take KFC, you can possibly link it with black people. Not that you wanted to, but because of the memes and biases. The stereotype problem so to say.\n\nSo it can be said that society is built against them, they are less likely to do valuable things as it\'s seen as odd for them to do it. They have to exert more force and against pressure, biases, first impressions, and all of that if they want to succeed, if they even start. The society is against their start, so many don\'t even try.\n\nThis is why it\'s a problem, and it\'s not weird for us, non-minority people to want to solve it, I mean, it\'s a real problem, why don\'t you want to solve it? Because they will *take our jobs*, I mean come one. Do you wan to suppress the minority and trash equality because you\'re afraid they\'ll take your future? Then work harder, it\'s as easy as that.\n\nWho doesn\'t want a job in tech? You earn a lot by writing code. Google. Apple. All of that.\n\nIt\'s not a coincidence that minority race is a less than minority in lucrative jobs. It\'s biases and other components that are against them.\n\nSame can be said about women in tech, and outside of tech, but not as much.','2017-12-06 22:29:37',1),('VZyLek0CwUxE','Waste of resources w.r.t. Society ','> We wanted flying cars but got 140 characters. — Peter Thiel\n\nIs Twitter, Instagram, Netflix, or even feminism useless waste of resources and time? I\'d like to think that\'s not the case\n\n#Feminism in tech is not a waste of resources. Currently, it\'s a male dominated field, and if we can get the remaining 50% of the population to learn computer science, we can increase the technology output by a lot. It could be an 100% increase in work force in tech, if the field had no bias toward women. Does not seem like a trivial useless thing at all. Rather a very, very good thing. We should encourage women to do great things, this will increase our innovation as a country. What good does it do to stop 50% of our population to stay at home or take the non-lucrative jobs that doesn\'t contribute much to society?\n\nAnother argument on feminism that they only want good jobs, well that\'s not a surprise. And it\'s a good thing, it\'s good that they want to contribute to society, how is that bad? It\'s partly because men want a less competitive field. Giving them an easier time is not unfair, rather, they\'ve been treated unfairly all this time s.t. it\'s impossible to make it fair at once. That\'s why they kind of need a head start. They should in the end still be judged fairly among all \"contestants\" though.\n\nI don\'t think that women inherently don\'t want fulfilling jobs. Everyone wants a fulfilling life, and so too does women. Who doesn\'t want a job where you sit and code and earn hundreds of thousands of dollars every year? It became this way in the first place because of bias, not because of what they really want. Men didn\'t like pink in the way that we inherently don\'t like it, but also because of how society says we shouldn\'t like it. It\'s a thing that can change. And it\'s a good change if we can get women to work in tech. It\'s a valuable field for society.\n\nIs #twitter a waste of resources then? Or Instagram? I don\'t think so. Of course we can always say this argument to almost everything excluding the most efficient thing to do. But reality is not that simple.  \nFirstly, we don\'t know what is the right field to invest in. Computers seemed like a joke but has changed the world. How valuable is feminism, or will be? It\'s hard to know. Of course one can argue that we put *way too much* resources in feminism, that is a reasonable and very likely. But to get innovation, it\'s not about putting all your eggs in one basket. You diversify and try many things, and some hits is enough. I think? Not sure. How should society invest their resources? Find the answer to this question.\n\n#draft','2017-12-19 16:34:36',1),('WJvxXb5aqXCv','Hej','*jafjfjlöadjfkslaöfjsöadf*\n\n**fsfsdf**\n\n#test','2017-12-08 20:19:13',2),('XHZPNUgujRDL','Not doing what\'s right','There\'s different cases of doing something wrong, with respect to the state of the mind. You know what you\'re doing is wrong, but still choose to do it because of various reason. Or you can do something but not even know that it\'s wrong.\n\nThe latter is far worse as you will justify it and be totally convinced that you\'re doing something that\'s not bad. Convincing someone that thinks this way can be hard, and much of the times it\'s hard to change their mind.\n\nIf you already know what you\'re doing something that\'s wrong but still choose too, that\'s bad, but can be less so if you have a \"good reason\". Not voting because you are focusing on more important issues or life choices is a valid response. We can\'t really expect everyone to vote, and there will be outliers.\n\n#draft','2017-12-12 01:31:42',1),('aVhO02fEn4an','First memory.','This is my first memory. Also a test. Hope it works like intended.','2017-11-04 00:24:40',1),('d0pXJv8NKSBt','Why you should vote','The voting system is based on the assumption that everyone votes. In many cases, the popular view can be the right view, depending on how the social is structured. If not enough people vote, the system break because a minority can push their own view.\n\nBut why should you vote? Because not voting breaks the system, and if everyone thinks like that, then of course nothing happens. But why can\'t I just get *k* number of people to vote, and not vote myself? In that case you almost surely must lie that you\'re going to vote, but will not in the end. And if that\'s the case, why can\'t everyone else do the same? We end up in the same situation like the last one. Thus, from a game theory perspective, the best action is to vote and get *k* number of people to vote. This way we can guarantee a higher probability of correct choice.','2017-12-12 01:26:31',1),('eZ9sUW5Mn0xc','Focus on the Days','Focus on the days, not the month or years. What I mean is that by getting the most of everyday will explicitly imply that you\'re efficient by month and years too.\n\nOptimizing days is far better than optimizing months or years. You can iterate faster and get a fine grained control over what you do. It\'s also better as an overview of how you\'re faring, if you average over a year, you might have holes of inefficiency which you really won\'t be able to spot. You remember days, not years.\n\nA wider topic of this is productivity. This is a subtopic on #productivity.','2017-12-18 17:04:42',1),('ht4B1qpi05gt','CryptoKitties','Cryptokitties is a Ethereum based service. You can buy cats for $ETH and then breed cats to get more cats. The developers pitch it as a collectible, but at the end of the day it\'s just another buy low sell high scheme. There\'s nothing backing it, just mindless investing.\n\nWhat\'s hidden beneath this behavior can be seen as identical to the crypto rush, where FOMO is the strongest force driving the price up. The developers probably understand this, and to make the cats more rare, they raise the breed fee from 0.002 to 0.015 which is a pretty big increase.\n\nCryptoKitties also made it even more obvious that Ethereum\'s Blockchain has limited transaction power. The backlog went up to a solid 15k tx in backlog. This would not be acceptable for irl situations and just shows that crypto is still early-adoption. **The price of cryptocurrencies is just crazy**. Sure, I agree that there\'s potential, but the current coins won\'t be the future winners. Just look at all early tech companies and none of them are still alive today. But, will the general public even adopt some new coin? I mean, Bitcoin is de-facto standard already, it\'s the coin everyone know about. *Ethereum? What nerdy shit is that?*\n\nBut crypto has potential. It can become something real. The hype will die down and that\'s the time to strike. Be there before the next cycle, much money still to be made. Pick the winners are you\'re rewarded. That\'s how it will be with the next big coin.','2017-12-05 15:26:17',1),('lEXQsPz7glc6','Minor flawes','Everyone has their own minor flaws, that\'s ok. But if you think it\'s a flaw, don\'t you want to correct them?\n\nI personally want to correct my minor flaws, but how do I do that, I mean, they\'re minor so how do I catch them? These minor seeming things are obvious for everyone else but yourself, that\'s what\'s so interesting about minor flaws. The fastest way to find them is by having other people point it out to you, but they don\'t want to do that. Who wants to seem like some stuck-up person and point out your flaw? What do they get? Nothing. The cons exists for pointing out minor flaws though, it\'s not that socially accepted. You\'re supposed to hold a social standard or contract when interacting with other people. But this contract doesn\'t have to hold with family and friends. That\'s why the only way to know is by family and friends.\n\nYou can set up a special type of contract where people solely point out each others problems, but that might not be that easy to implement as you behave differently when talking with strangers. You put on a mask, that\'s why this special contract won\'t work.\n\nThere is a way to fix minor flaws, and it\'s not by fixing minor flaws per-se. It\'s by picking up the traits you want, and disposing of the traits you don\'t want. You apply this process on people around you. Family, friends, idols, people on YouTube, whoever. With time, you\'ll have built up a well functioning behavior, but it will take time. Most people don\'t change overnight, almost none does. This method is from Warren Buffet. [1]\n\n[1]: https://youtu.be/xguK3x2HQXg?t=2m42s','2017-12-16 02:17:37',1),('lKqm8lBFZlDy','Companies started during slump','During the 2008 crash and the following economic recession, the most mind boggling companies were started. AirBnB just to name two of them. Later on we see even more startups like Stripe, and the whole on-demand economy. Of course much of it is low margin business, but still.\n\nIn recessions, the natural move people tend towards is doing nothing. Things are bad, why invest? But it shown that innovation still happens. The true forces of nature will push on. Why is that?\n\nAVC writes that get in before money shows up and out when it does. [1] But still, why? Why should one get out when money shows up? Without regard for whether you\'re an investor or a founder.\n\nIf there\'s no money in the sector, then it\'s either efficient or it\'s undervalued. So either way it\'s a pretty safe choice to invest in. No high risks. If you end up on the other end of the stick, it\'s not due to volatility or anything, huge part of it on you then. That is something that you can fix. You can get better at it, it\'s a game you can play. If you\'re in when there\'s no money, that also means that you will be able to ride the whole wave.\n\nBut let\'s say you get in the sector when there\'s already money, why don\'t you want this? Well, there\'s a high chance that you got in when the hype was in effect and the market is already inefficient, in the wrong direction. Of course it can still go up even if it\'s already inefficient, just look at cryptocurrencies. Insane stuff. Anyhow, how do you sell *before* the market gets efficient again? Depends. You have to time your sell right, much on luck.\n\nYou can only go up when there\'s no money with the chance that it becomes inefficient, while if it\'s already inefficient, you can only go down.\nBut if it\'s inefficient in a way that it\'s undervalued and people will understand that it\'s valuable, oh boy you\'re in for a ride.\n\n[1]: http://avc.com/2017/12/the-early-stage-slump/','2017-12-06 21:07:29',1),('nACiJ5Ot6sBb','Micro-transactions in Games','I just read this blog post about *Wilson Boxes*. [1] Basically, pay-to-win loot boxes popularized inside EA\'s games by the CEO Wilson. Some loot boxes are inherently *evil* in such a way that they take advantage of the human psyche. I won\'t go into detail which part of the human psyche, but we know for a fact that they do.\n\nWell then, how should game studios monetize their games? Not independent game studios, but rather big ones. The answer is that it depends. If you\'re not Riot Games with can make huge sums on skins, then it\'s hard to earn on micro-transactions in a nice way.\n\nLoot boxes is the easy way out and the lazy answer as you can literally slap it onto any game and make them add value for the player buying it, and boom. There you have a functioning micro-transaction that takes advantage of the human psyche. Add some addicting sound- and visual effects just to spice it up, and there you go. I have a deep disgust the the visual and sound effects for loot box like features. They\'re just so addicting for some reason.\n\nI need to write about how to monetize indie games in the future. It\'s an interesting subject as most of them strictly only make money on direct game sales. Itch.io is an interesting site, but still does not achieve the right product market fit. Steam is cool but UI really sucks, and is much closer to product market fit. I\'ll leave it at that.\n\n[1]: http://www.shamusyoung.com/twentysidedtale/?p=41164\n[1]: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PTLFNlu2N_M','2017-12-06 14:08:41',1),('nXn5Mmr9URdF','Bitcoin and Regret','Missing almost the whole Bitcoin train has been tough. But it\'s probably tough on many people. It\'s weird. How did it end up this way? Why did I now buy some Bitcoin? Hindsight 20/20 though.\n\nI feel anguish and regret. How did I miss this train, when I knew about it so early? Most tech people are probably in a similar seat as me. We have seen Bitcoin\'s rise since it\'s beginnings, and just watched as it passed by. Many of the tech people ignore everything that\'s going on around us and focus on what we find interesting. That\'s why we miss these big things going on. But the people early in these cycles are also never people who are searching for a big return, they always come late in the game. The cohort who are the first are the just interested people, not much else to it. That\'s also why the last decades it has been the rise of the *nerds*, we just do what interests us as side projects, and they blossom into these giant beasts that change the world, for better or worse. As much as this trait costs us, it can also favor us. This trait is similar to how venture capitalists work. Shoot a lot and you might hit big. Just shoot at many things you find interesting, don\'t think about it\'s future returns. But you need to actually shoot at things you do find interesting, I did fint Bitcoin interesting, but never gave it a shot. That\'s also what made a difference between a good *indie tech vc guy* and myself. But now I\'m gonna go down a different path. I\'m actually going to shoot and try to hit something. It\'s a hard balance but the most important point is to not stop shooting, whether it\'s