t _the breaking point_ for me, but rather the accumulation of past and current politically disturbing topics.\n\nFor my whole life I\'ve never really gotten in contact with politics that much as I don\'t watch TV and social medias didn\'t exists before, but now it\'s become even harder to not come in contact with politics. Everyone has now a voice because of Facebook, Twitter, and whatnot, and I\'m not sure if it\'s a good thing or not.\n\nPolitics, for some weird reason, is a topic that anyone can talk about without being entirely shutdown or in the wrong. You won\'t see many people that will talk about math, datascience or biology with the same confidence [1]. The entry-bar for political discussion is very low, and I pro-actively avoid giving my opinion on politics because I know for sure I\'m wrong in many places. It\'s not that I don\'t want to say my opinion, I sometimes do. It\'s just that I make sure I say with confidence that I\'m wrong with many problems and solutions. When I know I\'m wrong, I usually do not change my view to the inverse, but choose to throw away my opinion to become neutral and gradually converge to some standpoint.\n\nBut let\'s not stray too far from the main topic, I cut out politics because the cons outweigh the pros way too much. I have not become happier or much smarter because of politics, but rather the opposite. I do value politics, whether it\'s to make changes or fight absurdity to not repeat tragedies. The problem is that I have become very _paranoid_ that it\'s not worth it anymore.\n\nI\'m not and have never been a force of nature in politics, but always more of a standby-er (which most of us are). Instead I have chosen to double-down on other important problems that we face. Not everyone can be equally engaged in politics or should need too.\n\n[1]: From Paul Graham, good read. (http://www.paulgraham.com/identity.html)','2017-11-07 20:13:37',1),('zA5ZgWvNDOuo','Prostitution','Prostitution. Is it wrong? As in morally, for society and all of those relevant questions.\n\nProstitution is more stigmatized than it actually is. What harm does it *really* do to society? Not much to be honest. It just people that are too biased towards prostitution, not that it\'s necessarily their fault. I mean we all have our own biases, it\'s hard to be perfectly bias less. I once had a negative view on prostitution too, while now I\'m more neutral towards it. It has it\'s drawbacks but also it\'s upside. Upside does not necessarily mean contribute huge positive contribution to society either, it can mean freedom of selling their body.\n\nBut whether it should be legal is another question that I won\'t try to answer. There\'s much that can happen if it does become legal, I\'m not sure how to answer this.\n\nMy own bias towards prostitution has led me to believe strongly that I have many other biases that I have not noticed and have a hard time noticing. I must be more observant on myself. Expect an entry on biases sometime in the future.','2017-12-06 21:13:49',1);
